International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 13 Jan 2012
Source: OIE, WAHID (World Animal Health Information Database), weekly disease information 2012; 25(3) [edited]
http://web.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=single_report&pop=1&reportid=11487


African swine fever, South Africa
---------------------------------
Information received on (and dated) 13 Jan 2012 from Dr Bothle Michael Modisane, chief director, Department of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries, Animal Production and Health, Pretoria, South Africa

Report type: immediate notification
Start date: 3 Jan 2012
Date of 1st confirmation of the event: 6 Jan 2012
Date submitted to OIE: 13 Jan 2012
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: January 2011
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: African swine fever virus
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to the whole country

New outbreaks
Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1 (ASF_2012_001): ASF_2012_001, Delmas, Mpumalanga
Date of start of the outbreak: 3 Jan 2012
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Swine / 80 / 35 / 28 / 52 / 0
Affected population: pigs found to be sick at an abattoir in Gauteng. No pigs left on farm and abattoir also empty.

Outbreak statistics (percentages)
Species / Apparent morbidity rate / Apparent mortality rate / Apparent case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Swine / 43.75 / 35 / 80 / 100
* Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive
Epidemiological comments: outbreak occurred outside South Africa's ASF control zone. The source of the outbreak is being investigated.

Control measures
Measures applied: stamping out; quarantine; movement control inside the country; disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s); no vaccination; no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type: Transboundary Animal Diseases Programme, ARC-OVI (national laboratory)
Tests and results
Species / Test / Test date / Result
Swine / polymerase chain reaction (PCR) / 6 Jan 2012 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Based on OIE-WAHID reports African swine fever continues to be present in the Central African Republic, Chad, Kenya, South Africa, and Tanzania whilst the disease is listed as endemic in Nigeria; see http://web.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=disease_immediate_summary&disease_type=Terrestrial&disease_id=12.

The last outbreak of ASF in South Africa occurred in September 2001 (see ProMED-mail report no. 20010810.1893. - Mods.NM/FE

As noted in the epidemiological comments in the OIE report, this outbreak is marginally outside the South African ASF control zones. The African swine fever control zone spans the northern part of the county and includes areas in Limpopo, Mpumalanga, and North West provinces as can be seen on the map at http://www.nda.agric.za/vetweb/epidemiology/Disease%20Maps/ASFcopy.pdf.

Maps of South Africa can be seen at http://healthmap.org/r/1Fey and http://www.sa-venues.com/maps/south-africa-provinces.htm. The location of outbreak can be seen on the map included in the OIE report at the source URL above. - Mods.FE/NM/PC]
